1 Behavioral Health of the Department of Health and Human
2 Services, adopt an emergency response plan to address opioid-
3 related drug overdoses at the institution. Such an emergency
4 response plan must include, without limitation:
5 (a) Plans for providing education on opioid-related drug
6 overdoses;
7 (b) Measures to respond compassionately to opioid-related
8 drug overdoses, including, without limitation:
9 (1) Emphasizing rescue breathing techniques; and
10 (2) Utilizing naloxone hydrochloride in the lowest dosage
11 effective to restore breathing;
12 (c) Procedures for the distribution and administration of
13 opioid antagonists, including, without limitation, ensuring ease of
14 access to opioid antagonists; and
15 (d) Provisions ensuring that a student will not be subject to
16 disciplinary action by the institution for obtaining an opioid
17 antagonist.
18 2. Each institution within the System may tailor the
19 emergency response plan described in subsection 1 to meet the
20 needs and capacity of the institution for implementing the plan. In
21 tailoring an emergency response plan, an institution may
22 determine:
23 (a) Whether training related to the plan will be provided in
24 person or virtually and synchronously or asynchronously;
25 (b) The locations at the institution where opioid antagonists
26 will be accessible; and
27 (c) The manner in which opioid antagonists will be distributed
28 at the institution.
29 3. An emergency response plan described in subsection 1 may
30 not require a person to complete any training in order to obtain or
31 administer an opioid antagonist.
32 4. The Board of Regents may adopt a model emergency
33 response plan that meets the requirements of this section to assist
34 institutions in developing their emergency response plans
35 pursuant to subsection 1. The Board of Regents may not require
36 an institution to utilize the model emergency response plan.
37 5. As used in this section:
38 (a) “Opioid antagonist” has the meaning ascribed to it in
39 NRS 453C.040.
40 (b) “Opioid-related drug overdose” has the meaning ascribed
41 to it in NRS 453C.050.
42 Sec. 2. This act becomes effective upon passage and approval.
